	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Leadiin,<BR>
  Hiyas bud.  Thought you might find this post most interesting.  Just pasting it here in its entirity to give due credit to its author.  Enjoy.<BR>
<BR>
Kablooey<BR>
Unregistered User  Subject: RE: &quot;SoW Me&quot; WTF is that?<BR>
 posted 8/6/2000 6:37:00 PM      <BR>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<BR>
I've never charged for a SOW either, and often heal people. I usually spend at least a solid half-hour of every session I'm on doing nothing but SOWing and healing and buffing people, just for fun. <BR>
Unless you're the other guy, you don't know what he does or why or when, and it's presumptuous for anyone to think they do. Not only does nobody owe anyone anything, but you don't know how much of a price they've already paid to strangers because you're not following them around all day long. If a druid doesn't SOW or buff or heal you, you have no idea if he doesn't do it to others or hasn't been doing it for quite a bit that day or that week. One thing you DO know is he gets more requests than any class in the game for his buffs -- to presume they don't get overwhelming and tiresome would be absurd. It would also smack of more than a little selfishness and greed to assume that, although he is going to have to turn down some or all strangers at some point, you of all people should be the one never denied his time and effort at a moment's notice. Once again, you are not OWED anything, and in no position to make judgments about his generosity because chances are you aren't around following him around.<BR>
<BR>
When it comes to what people deserve and who should be granting favors or giving out things, why do we always think of the other guy first? Why don't we clean up our own houses instead of leaping joyously at the opportunity to criticize others? Instead of whining that strangers don't bust their humps spending more time and energy on us, why don't we just try to be decent with other players rather than demanding of them, try to not be resentful and constantly carrying a chip on our shoulders for who-knows-what-real-or-imagined-slight-this-time, and if we feel the world or the EQ world or whatever needs to be a better place, put up or shut up instead -- start doing more things for others instead of trying to be the first and loudest on the bullhorn screaming at strangers. <BR>
<BR>
Having too much fun being judgmental is a character flaw -- especially if it is based on an incomplete understanding of the situation or a lack of desire to gain an understanding of it. People who judge all druids by referring to one druid, or do so without any attempt to put themselves in the place of druids or understand what they are talking about should clean the wax out of their ears and wise up. When your class has to play anonymously, like druids do -- the only class that has to do so -- then you can start saying what druids should or shouldn't do, because then at least you'll have some understanding of what goes on. <BR>
<BR>
Why anyone feels they have the right to control other people's time and how they use it has always been beyond me anyway. Funny how the impulse behind telling others to &quot;be nice&quot; or &quot;be generous&quot; is generally the opposite of either niceness or generosity. If it's not going to be just a relentless con game that drags everybody down to the lowest level of the gripers, try being generous and nice yourself for a change. <BR>
<BR>
Here are a few suggestions:<BR>
<BR>
1) Tanks - stop looting everything the party kills before the healers and casters even get a chance. Just because you are physically closest to the monsters doesn't give you absolute rights over them -- and just because the casters and healers you are with are sitting down medding doesn't mean they don't want any loot all night. They're just doing their job -- part of which is saving your butt. Keep yourself first in line for healing or having the monsters mezzed in your vicinity before others elsewhere are mezzed by not being a jerk about looting. Word to the wise. This tip would seem to be obvious, but like most obvious things, it is hidden in clear sight.<BR>
<BR>
I can fight for hours and hours as the main healer of my group and get virtually no loot whatever. Meanwhile, people are saying, excuse me, I have to go to town to sell this stuff. They sometimes even want the group to halt its fighting while I, broke so far that evening, port them out to sell all the stuff they never let me have a crack at. This can go on for level after level, when you're in pick-up groups. Wonder why druids charge for some things? How'd you like to fight for a week and have just about nothing to show for it, while the people you're with are making big bucks? Why, good lord, it's enough to make a guy charge for teleports!<BR>
<BR>
2) People of all classes -- don't loot during the fight! I don't know how many times I've seen this go on. It means you don't care about the survival of your group or its respect. At the very least, it shows you are unfocused on important things when you most need to be focused -- and that your services are only really partially available...you're free when you're not busy looting. At worst, it's just cravenly disrespectful of the needs and welfare of your party and laughably greedy.<BR>
<BR>
3) Clerics and other casters with beneficial spells -- if you beg a druid for SOW or a port or whatever, why not bestow some of your own buffs on him? Clerics and shamans have great buffs, and I rarely see them given in exchange for the freebie buffs I give. Why is that? If my mana is good enough for you, the least you could do is give something back. Enchanters have clarity and breeze, and usually they're nice about giving it out, too, but I'm always puzzled when they don't. It's not like they don't know it's needed by another caster -- especially one whose mana they just used for free.<BR>
<BR>
Here's another:<BR>
<BR>
Ubertwinks carrying 1000 plat, auctioning off fantastic items, and then begging druids for freebies because they're a low or semi-low level is kinda silly. I only wish I had as much plat as the people begging me for freebies a lot of the time. A guy carrying around a sword worth a couple hundred plat is someone I frankly don't feel is in a hard place in his EQ life. I don't mind twinking your character, but why twink me? You're the last guy who either needs freebies or should have the guts to beg for them. <BR>
<BR>
Here's another:<BR>
<BR>
I'm exhausted. Wake up and realize what other screwy things you're doing yourself, and knock it off. The things posted above are the rule, not the exception, so not many people I meet in the game could say they don't apply to them -- I'm sure the ones screaming the loudest that they never do that are probably the ones embarassed that they've been noticed. Yes, people notice, even if they don't say anything. <BR>
<BR>
Keep it up, and druids might charge you double, or give you nothing. And remember, while the druid can solo all through his career, you can't, and you'll need him. Better not stiff him now or you're burning your bridges even before you've crossed them.<BR>
<BR>
[This message has been edited by Kablooey (edited 08-08-2000).]<BR>
<BR>
 
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
